children.subject: We will add more very soon (as in a few days).  However, to be a bit more clear as this is always a point of confusion.  The class currently has 75 enrolled in CS160 and 10 enrolled in CS260A for a total of 85 students in this class.  So the added seats will be set such that (# of students in CS160) + (# of students in CS260A) <= 120.  We will not add 45 more seats to CS160 to be clear. Thanks.
Has the course size been increased yet? Berkeleytime says there are 75 people enrolled in 160 and 6 in 260A, which are still the same enrollment numbers as when this was posted.
Class size increased months ago so no further expansion will happen.
At what point will the class become 120 seats instead of the current 75?
No guarantees but likely. I'm going to contact instructors about possibly expanding once I'm done opening F19 classes.
on a relevant note, I'm on waitlist 16 for the summer cs 160, do I have a shot at getting off the waitlist?

Is there any possible way to get into 160 if we aren't already enrolled/waitlisted? My enrollment as a declared CS major wasn't until yesterday so I am very bummed that it seems impossible to get into the course though it worked very well with my plan for the semester.
Will the Fall 2019 instructors be using Android SDK?
In sequential order based on wait list position as seats become available.
for clarification, how are available seats prioritized between the 160 waitlist and the 260 waitlist?
How is the waitlist processed between CS160 and CS260?

Do we know when the larger format of the class will be offered? I am assuming not Spring 2020, but could you elaborate if you have more iinfo? Also, what are the chances of a CS minor being able to get into the class Spring 2020? Thanks!

history.content:
TLTR:

I am not teaching CS160 in the Fall. It will be taught by leading industrial HCI researchers. Enrollment will be capped at 120 students.


Details:

First a bit of background. CS160 has grown from 80 students just 5 years ago to well over 200+ in Fall 2015, Spring 2016, and Fall 2018 (it typically runs at 120 students in Spring semesters and summer). Please understand that we are working very hard to accommodate as many students as we can for this course and we are as excited about teaching it as you are to engage in the material and create great HCI projects.

For Fall 2019 several factors limit the enrollment. The first is room size. The course will be held in 310 Jacobs Hall which has a 120 capacity. I realize many of you will ask why we don't expand it by webcasting and video recording the course. We have offered versions of that in the past but they were unsuccessful. I also know many of you will ask again why not just expand it. We are well aware that many CS courses grow well beyond room capacity size. One reason is that this is a high touch design focused computer science course and requires us to all be together for classroom activities not just uploading code and assignments on bCourses. We are absolutely exploring ways to expand this course. However, accepting all the students or even another 100 will significantly dilute the learning experience for everyone (not to mention making it unmanageable from a teaching staff perspective). Will it be offered in larger format in the future – likely...but not Fall 2019. I do want to make all of you aware that CS160 is taught every semester AND summer (yes even this summer there is a fantastic offering of CS160).

The second reason is that I will not be teaching CS160 in Fall 2019. While the content and syllabus in terms of HCI methods, design, etc will remain the same, I will not be involved in teaching CS160 in the Fall. It will be taught by a leading HCI industrial researcher team from Siemens Research here in Berkeley. I have personally worked with this group, I have met with them over the detailed planning and operation of CS160. I have also personally selected an extremely talented cohort of teaching staff for Fall 2019 – (GSIs and Readers who have all taken CS160, all have GSI experience, many even previous GSIs for CS160 with me!). It will indeed be an excellent offering allowing students to learn HCI and gain insight from leading industrial HCI researchers. However, (and you will see this reflected in past offerings of CS160 when taught by non-UC Berkeley faculty such as researchers from Microsoft, etc) we cap course enrollment at lower levels. For this semester we will cap class enrollment at 120. There will be a smaller waitlist to meet expectations. The course will not be webcast and we will not be expanding the course beyond 120. I encourage many of you to take CS160 in the summer or again there will be a Spring 2020 offering. Thanks for your interest in HCI!

Eric Paulos
Associate Professor
EECS, UC Berkeley
